@cgraywang Gluon NLP is after all the NLP package for Gluon.

@astonzhang I'm not sure why you think the API change in gluonnlp would be higher than the contrib package in mxnet. If you freeze the version of gluonnlp/mxnet you depend, then neither would change. If you track the head for either package, they are equally likely to change, with one exception for the particular case of text: it's likely that features in contrib package will be dropped at some point, while it's unlikely to happen for gluonnlp.

Both dmlc/gluon-nlp and dmlc/gluon-cv are resources that you can use to simplify the tutorials, as was illustrated by the comparison between the linked tutorial above and the proposed notebook. Besides simplicity, in this particular case, you can freeze the version you use for gluonnlp (i.e. 0.2), whereas you can't do the same for mxnet as long as the repo depends on nightly builds.

Since we can't easily withdraw printed copies of a book, I'd suggest we either drop experimental APIs altogether, or at least pick one that doesn't expire easily.

@szha 

In the long run, MXNet/Gluon is also unstable, which will cause some code in the book to break. For instance, we fixed some code in the book after MXNet is updated from 20180403 to 20180423. Hence, we will clarify in the book that code may change, including any possible future changes to mxnet.contrib. Thus, it is fine to use mxnet.contrib, even if it may change in the future.

As we discussed, gluonnlp will be merged into gluon. In that case, I don't think we will maintain both gluon.nlp and gluonnlp. Likely, we deprecate gluonnlp then it may be confusing to mention gluonnlp in the book.

